./.title: Code for Philly - Partnership Guide
./.body:
Code for Philly - Partnership Guide
This document will help you get started with creating a new project at Code for Philly.
Code for Philly is an organization that facilitates collaboration between non-profits and technical volunteers. Partnerships are the lifeblood of our organization.
A partnership might include:

Forming a new relationship with a non-profit organization in Philly.
Rallying volunteers to support a partner's active project.
Securing sponsorship for our weekly meeting spaces or larger events.

You can create meaningful partnerships here
Whether you work at a non-profit, are a coding wizard, or hate technology--there is a valuable role for you in shaping collaboration at Code for Philly!

creating-new-partnerships/defining-the-p.title: Defining the partnership
creating-new-partnerships/defining-the-p.body:
Defining the partnership
Partnerships at Code for Philly help volunteers stay connected with important issues in the city, mobilize where support is needed, and ensure we can provide regular space for collaboration.
The first step of defining a partnership is deciding what kind of opportunity it might open up:

Relationship - you want to raise awareness around a compelling non-profit. They may not need many volunteers yet, but an introduction to Code for Philly leadership, or a single volunteer to coordinate sharing their mission at a meetup.
Active Project - what people often associate with Code for Philly. This is when volunteers support a project run by a partner. Depending on the project's needs, it could rally many volunteers, or only a single volunteer.
Sponsorship - sponsors enable Code for Philly to facilitate volunteer work. This occurs through hosting weekly space for presentations, or providing financial sponsorship for larger events.
